`ConduytSerial` over `Serial` is the simplest transport. No modules, no datastreams: the host controls every pin individually.

```cpp
#include <Conduyt.h>

ConduytSerial transport(Serial, 115200);
ConduytDevice device("PicoBasic", "1.0.0", transport);

void setup() {
  device.begin();
}

void loop() {
  device.poll();
}
```

`pin().subscribe()` is an async iterable; `for await` yields each reading.

```ts
import { ConduytDevice } from 'conduyt-js'
import { SerialTransport } from 'conduyt-js/transports/serial'

const device = await ConduytDevice.connect(
  new SerialTransport({ path: '/dev/ttyACM0' })
)

for await (const reading of device.pin(1).subscribe({ mode: 'analog', intervalMs: 100 })) {
  console.log(reading)
}
```

Datastreams are typed and named; the read-only flag (`false` writable) means the host subscribes, not writes.

```cpp
#include <Conduyt.h>

ConduytSerial transport(Serial, 115200);
ConduytDevice device("TempNode", "1.0.0", transport);

uint32_t lastPush = 0;

void setup() {
  device.addDatastream("temperature", CONDUYT_FLOAT32, "celsius", false);
  device.begin();
}

void loop() {
  device.poll();
  if (millis() - lastPush >= 2000) {
    lastPush = millis();
    float fakeT = 20.0f + (millis() % 10000) / 1000.0f;
    device.writeDatastream("temperature", fakeT);
  }
}
```

```ts
import { ConduytDevice } from 'conduyt-js'
import { SerialTransport } from 'conduyt-js/transports/serial'

const device = await ConduytDevice.connect(
  new SerialTransport({ path: '/dev/ttyACM0' })
)

for await (const value of device.datastream('temperature').subscribe()) {
  console.log(`T=${value.toFixed(2)} C`)
}
```

Module enable macros come before the include. Writable datastreams (4th arg `true`) accept host writes; the handler receives a payload reader.

```cpp
#define CONDUYT_MODULE_NEOPIXEL
#include <Conduyt.h>
#include <Adafruit_NeoPixel.h>

const int NEOPIXEL_PIN = 48;
Adafruit_NeoPixel pixel(1, NEOPIXEL_PIN, NEO_GRB + NEO_KHZ800);

ConduytSerial transport(Serial, 115200);
ConduytDevice device("PixelNode", "1.0.0", transport);

void onColor(ConduytPayloadReader &p, ConduytContext &ctx) {
  uint32_t rgb = p.readUInt32();
  pixel.setPixelColor(0, rgb);
  pixel.show();
  ctx.ack();
}

void setup() {
  pixel.begin();
  pixel.setBrightness(40);
  device.addDatastream("led_color", CONDUYT_UINT32, "rgb", true);
  device.onDatastreamWrite("led_color", onColor);
  device.begin();
}

void loop() {
  device.poll();
}
```

`onConnect` runs after the host's HELLO handshake. The Conduyt API surfaces the negotiated context.

```cpp
#include <Conduyt.h>

ConduytSerial transport(Serial, 115200);
ConduytDevice device("kitchen-thermo", "1.0.0", transport);

void onConnected() {
  Serial.println("host connected");
}

void setup() {
  device.onConnect(onConnected);
  device.begin();
}

void loop() {
  device.poll();
}
```

`MockTransport` exposes the bytes the device would have received, so tests can assert against the wire protocol without real hardware.

```ts
import { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest'
import { ConduytDevice } from 'conduyt-js'
import { MockTransport } from 'conduyt-js/transports/mock'

describe('pin write', () => {
  it('sends a digital-write command for pin 13 high', async () => {
    const transport = new MockTransport()
    const device = await ConduytDevice.connect(transport)

    await device.pin(13).mode('output')
    await device.pin(13).write(1)

    const written = transport.sent
    expect(written.length).toBeGreaterThan(0)
    // last frame should be a PIN_WRITE on pin 13 with value 1
    const last = written[written.length - 1]
    expect(last).toContain(13)
    expect(last).toContain(1)
  })
})
```
